The length os the foregoing summary os the De Officio Regis may perhaps be excused as an attempt to exhibit the general arguments os the treatise in their due connexion with the many incidental topics os interest which osten threaten to obscure them. The scholastic dissertations on Honour and Obedience, the invective against the abuse ol Excommunication, the attacks on the Civil and Canon Laws, the exposition os the wicked- ness of unjust Wars, all ol these have their independent interest, and at times divert attention from Wyclif's main subject—his conception of the rights and duties oi an English King. The more we examine this concep- tion the more reason we shall find to admire it, at any rate on its political side. It is thoroughly patriotic‚ and it is thoroughly constitutional‚ and again and again we find in Wyclif's arguments, despite their medieval clothing, the principles by which Englishmen have been guided in the greatest crises os their national history. An English King must be supreme in his own land against both Pope and Emperor. The English Common Law is as good and better than the Roman. Foreigners · who enjoy the protection ol the English king must be loyally obedient to his authority. Again the King is supreme as over his own subjectS, and in the enunciation oi the absolute obedience due to him there seems at first something very little in accordance with the course of English history. But obedience, as Wyclif viewed it, has many sides. It will not allow its object to do wrong, and may lawlully take the form of resistance to tyranny, even to the point of putting the tyrant to death.
